			<!-- Begin News/Information Section -->
				<table border="0" width="100%" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" ID="Table23">
					<tr id="trmasthead">
						<td valign="middle" class="main_font" align="center">
							<font size="3"><b>&nbsp;</b></font>
					    </td>
					</tr>
					
					   <td>

			
			
			


<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">

		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Bindolaf's Cleric Guide-Tarew Marr</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:tdoum@med.auth.gr">Bindolaf</a> | 
		            7/27/1999 4:25:43 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">So! You have decided to pursue the ways of the Holy Man or Woman! So have I. To aid you in your quest, here are a few tips on how to proceed. Follow them or do not. They are offered caringly anyway.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
First of all let me warn you, not meaning to deter anyone from becoming a Cleric:<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Do not become a Cleric if you want to solo, be able to take and deal damage, cast powerful offensive spells. Become a Warrior or a Wizard instead.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Now that we are past the basics, let us start at the beginning.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
RACE<BR>
What race you choose doesn't make a world of a difference, still there are some unique features to each race, that you must have in mind. Taking the Human race as &quot;baseline&quot; I'd say that High Elves are weaker but perhaps wiser, whereas Dwarves are both stronger and wiser. In a nutshell I'd suggest that Dwarven Clerics are best suited for some -some mind you, not extensive- melee and have enough wisdom to make perfect Clerics. On the downside, they lack agility and charisma, making them easier targets. Humans make a good choice for two reasons. First of all they gain experience quicker and secondly they start in Freeport (certainly my first choice) or Qeynos, cities that have good newbie areas and nearby harder zones, nicely balanced. Disperse your extra points among features you find lacking keeping in mind that Wisdom is your main attribute (it controls your initial mana points and mana gain per level).<BR>
<BR>
EQUIPMENT<BR>
Weapons<BR>
<BR>
Clerics traditionally (or at least in the AD&amp;D environment) cannot and are not allowed to use sharp (slashing or piercing) weapons. Thus they carry, use and fight with blunt weapons. These are mainly maces, hammers and staves. The following lines might be a bit of a spoiler to some (though I do not think so) but anyway I'll tell you. Find a one handed blunt weapon to begin with. The only choice -in that it is the best choice- is the Cracked Staff. It is found on creatures as low level as decaying skeletons, so that should not be a problem. The cracked staff will serve you well ntil you reach level 10 or so. Upgrade to another staff or warhammer according to your likings, but be warned that you will eventually need to use Two handed blunt weapons, like the very good Glowing Crook, or the Fine Steel Great Staff (further down you'll find tips on how to advance your skills). Next is...<BR>
<BR>
Armor<BR>
<BR>
I cannot stress the importance of wearing decent armor enough. Indicatory towards the necessity of armor is the fact that Clerics are allowed and can wear even the strongest and heaviest pieces of armor (plate). Tip: Many blacksmiths have come forth selling their own player-created armor items (Banded Armor) at surprisingly -even ridiculous- prices. Start by buying Patchwork Armor -very cheap but good for a newbie nonetheless- and then once you have the money start buying pieces of Banded Armor. Do not spend money on Leather Armor or Chainmail Armor bought in stores from NPC's.<BR>
<BR>
SPELLS<BR>
Bear always in mind that the Cleric is primarily a Healer and to a lesser degree a bestower of Divine Gifts. Also, you will be warned that Clerics gain Spell Circles (new spells) every five (5) levels instead of every four (4). This is to compensate for the Clerics ability to wear armor and fight. A Cleric must buy armor and weapons on top of having to buy his spells, so let me offer some advice I consider important: Save money in order to be able to buy the next circle spells. It is no good getting to level 49 and to be still trying to buy those expensive level 29 spells. Also it is important to know which spell you need to buy as soon as you get your circle and what spells you may postpone purchasing until you have much much more money. A short guide will follow.<BR>
<BR>
Level One<BR>
<BR>
At level one you get Minor Healing and Courage, two spells that will serve you well for 4 levels. Immediately once you have the money go and buy Divine Aura and Strike. DA grants you invulnerability for a few seconds allowing you to escape a difficult situation (you cannot fight or cast spells while invulnerable) and Strike may be used as a finishing spell on retreating creatures, or -usually- as the first attack that will attract the creature. The rest of the 1st level spells are not really necessary, but if you have the money, buy them after you buy the essential Level Five (5)spells<BR>
<BR>
Level Five<BR>
<BR>
Many nice things to buy here. Light Healing is a must and so is Holy Armor, Gate, Ward Undead, Furor, Cure Disease and Summon Drink. A great many eh? Did you save money to buy them? If not, things might get harder. Note that Ward Undead does 34 points of damage to the Undead, giving you an edge against them. Use the spell to hunt skeletons, zombies etc.<BR>
<BR>
Level Nine<BR>
<BR>
Level Nine on the contrary does not have much that is useful. So you may start saving for the Level 14 goodies. Still do not forget to purchase Center, Root and Summon Food. Center is a very good &quot;buffer&quot; (a spell that raises your stats) giving you extra hit points.<BR>
<BR>
Level Fourteen<BR>
<BR>
Another good level, a turning point for the Cleric. Buy Healing, Smite, Bind Affinity, Expulse Undead and Symbol of Transal. Note that each of those spells cost eight and a half platinum for a grand total of 40pp. Have fun!<BR>
<BR>
HOW TO PLAY THE GAME<BR>
This is the part I consider most important. You might be a heavily armored, staff wielding, level 50 Cleric and still get yourself and -most importantly your Team- killed. I'll try to summarize my experiences from playing both in teams and solo.<BR>
<BR>
Team or solo?<BR>
<BR>
This is a good question to have answered before you start your character, as I have mentioned before. Why? It's simple. In my humble opinion a Cleric is not very good at soloing. At the lower levels, of course, you will be able to kill creatures hard enought to get you advanced real quickly. Especially at level 5 the &quot;Ward Undead&quot; spell boosts a Cleric to levels of gameplay not easily experienced by other classes. The magic fades at level 9-10 when the tougest creature a Cleric can best is &quot;blue-upper hand&quot;. You'll die a lot from creatures that Warriors around you reduce to mincemeat with relative ease. I do not want to say anything further on the subject, so I'll advise you to solo as far as you can (I'd say level 9-10) and then join a group. Joining a group has multiple benefits. First you get popular. A good Cleric is always needed by groups of any size and level. Secondly ou'll get experience MUCH faster. A warrior will be tanking (=no damage to you) and you will be assisting with heals, cures, buffs. At first team up with one person, preferably a GOOD tank, like a Barbarian Warrior, or a well armored Paladin or Bard. If you'd like to venture into dungeons, form LARGE groups (full is best).<BR>
<BR>
How to play-what to do<BR>
<BR>
First of all -and this is a personal plea as well as a (good I think) piece of advice- please please please DO NOT spend your mana like there is no tommorrow. I have seen too many trigger-happy Clerics. Casting their newly-gotten &quot;Smite&quot; spell 3-4 times in a row, inflicting good deals of damage. You know what happens to them? 99% of the cases they run out of mana just as the second or third creature approaches them. Then the tanks do battle with no healing backup, then someone shouts &quot;RUN!&quot; or &quot;ZONE!&quot;. Everyone runs. And you know who gets killed? No it's not the Warrior, warriors have 600, 700, 1000 hit points. No, the Cleric bites the dust (and the Wizard before him). So, please be careful. Use mana sparingly. Do not cast offensive spells, unless you really need to attract a beast (and then cast a lower circle spell, not the latest mana consuming brute you just bought) or you need to finish off a monster that's running. Other than those two cases, use only healing spells.<BR>
<BR>
Healing while not fighting<BR>
<BR>
When just sitting around, things are easy. Or so they seem. Follow a few guidelines and you'll be ok. While waiting, cast all but also only the necessary &quot;buffer&quot; spells. So you will cast &quot;Center&quot; and &quot;Holy Armor&quot; etc. on yourself and on all the spellcasters, but not necessarily on the warriors in the group (too much mana loss-downtime). This does not apply if you are fighting creatures very much higher than your average level. It also does not apply if the team is two persons. Yourself and -say- a warrior. If that is the case, courtesy if nothing else demands that you &quot;buff&quot; him/her up too. Healing. If you are &quot;camping&quot; or &quot;fetching&quot; try this trick: Heal everyone until they have 4 out of 5 life bubbles full. You will find, that until the next creature is spawned or attracted, their health will have been fully restored. Readjust this technique as you (and the team) advance levels. This is quite necessary as at first one bubble might mean 40 hp, but at higher levels it will be 200 or even more hit points. Nota Bene: Before resuming the hunt get your spell points to 80% of maximum by meditating (the same applies here...until you get the next creature, your mana will have gotten to 90 or even more %. Again adjust at higher levels). If you are in a dungeon and on the move, heal and meditate as you see fit, keeping in mind that there is no other rule than: &quot;NEVER run out of mana in a tight spot!&quot; Remember: Teams might not need the Cleric as a fighter, but they depend on him/her to heal.<BR>
<BR>
Healing while fighting<BR>
<BR>
As I said before, in-battle healing is a Cleric's highpoint. Do not start healing indiscriminantly. Heal weaker characters first. Usually start healing when a character is at 40-50% of his/her life. And then, DO NOT FULLY HEAL! Just enough so that they may complete the battle with relative safety. Heal spellcasters instantly as they tend to die rather quickly. Leave Warriors last. You will be surprised how much pain and brutality they can absorb :)<BR>
<BR>
In general...<BR>
<BR>
Do not run around much. Stick to your team's back row. I have seen spellcasters attract huge trains thus killing themselves, their teams and in many cases a great part of the zone's other players, who go around minding their own businesses.<BR>
Roleplay! Be nice, be kind and helpful. Do not kill steal, swear, in general do not do things a Cleric wouldn't do. Heal and buff players for NO charge and say nice things to them.<BR>
Do not be greedy. It might seem like a good idea to loot everything and execute grab-the-shiny-brass-halberd-and-run stunts, but you will find that soon noone will be willing to team up with you. And then you will have to either abandon the character (advisable) or go on soloing, which is extremely hard.<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
[top][RACE][EQUIPMENT][SPELLS][HOW TO]<BR>
<BR>
All this having been said, I want to thank you brave ones for reading through the whole boring thing, and to dare you ;) to send feedback: Objections (I suppose I'll be getting lots of those), suggestions, anything. Also if yo want to see me/pk me in the game, conact Bindolaf the Dwarf on Tarew Marr.<BR>
<BR>

			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
			</td>
